      <![CDATA[<h1 id="Chapter1-Shell"><a href="#Chapter1-Shell" class="headerlink" title="Chapter1: Shell"></a>Chapter1: Shell</h1><h2 id="What-is-it"><a href="#What-is-it" class="headerlink" title="What is it"></a>What is it</h2><h3 id="From-histoty-needs-why-was-shell-born"><a href="#From-histoty-needs-why-was-shell-born" class="headerlink" title="From histoty&amp;needs:why was shell born?"></a>From histoty&amp;needs:why was shell born?</h3><ol><li>Early Computers: No “Interface” at All</li><li>After the Emergence of Operating Systems: An “Entry” Was Needed</li><li>Shell Was Born to Meet This Need</li></ol><h3 id="Formal-Definition-What-Exactly-Is-Shell"><a href="#Formal-Definition-What-Exactly-Is-Shell" class="headerlink" title="Formal Definition: What Exactly Is Shell?"></a>Formal Definition: What Exactly Is Shell?</h3><pre><code>Def: Shell is a Command-Line Interpreter(CLI). It&#39;s a interface program between users and the operating system kernel. It&#39;s actually an **ordinary application** that runs dependent on the kernel and cannot exist dependently of the operating system</code></pre><h2 id="Why-it-matters"><a href="#Why-it-matters" class="headerlink" title="Why it matters"></a>Why it matters</h2><ol><li>The Bridge Connecting Users and the Kernel</li><li>The Core Tool for Automated Operation and Maintenance and Development</li><li>An Indispensable Means for Server and Remote Management</li><li>Improve Work Efficiency</li></ol><h2 id="Prerequisites"><a href="#Prerequisites" class="headerlink" title="Prerequisites"></a>Prerequisites</h2><h2 id="How-it-works-principles-mechanism"><a href="#How-it-works-principles-mechanism" class="headerlink" title="How it works (principles &#x2F; mechanism)"></a>How it works (principles &#x2F; mechanism)</h2><ol><li>Read input: Get your command.</li><li>Parse &amp; split: Separate command, argument, symbols.</li><li>Locate program: Search via PATH environment variable.</li><li>Create child process: Call system to run it.</li><li>wait for excution: Kernel runs and return output.</li><li>Display result: Shell formats and prints output.</li><li>Return to prompt: Wait for next command.</li></ol><h2 id="Step-by-step-tutorial"><a href="#Step-by-step-tutorial" class="headerlink" title="Step-by-step tutorial"></a>Step-by-step tutorial</h2><h3 id="Make-a-shell-script"><a href="#Make-a-shell-script" class="headerlink" title="Make a shell script"></a>Make a shell script</h3><ol><li>Using .h as filename extension(no influence on the excution of the script, just to know the type)</li><li>example:  <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">#!/bin.bash</span><br><span class="line">echo &quot;Hello World !&quot;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure> <code>#!</code> is used to tell which kinda shell is being used.</li><li>Ways to excute shell script:<ol><li>As excutable program: save the code as XXX.sh, cd to the corresponding directory  <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">chmod +x ./XXX.sh #使脚本具有执行权</span><br><span class="line">./XXX.sh #执行脚本（在环境变量中寻找该路径）</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li>Directly run the interpreter, with its parameter being the file name of the shell script, for example: <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">/bin/sh test.sh</span><br><span class="line">/bin/php test.php</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li></ol></li></ol><h3 id="Shell-variable"><a href="#Shell-variable" class="headerlink" title="Shell variable"></a>Shell variable</h3><ol><li><p>In Shell programming, variables are names used to store data values. When defining variables, do not add the dollar sign ($, required for variables in PHP), for example:</p> <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">your_name=&quot;New Jeans&quot;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>The rules of naming a variable:</p><ol><li>Including characters(Case-sensitive), numbers and _ only</li><li>Cannot start with a number</li><li>No key words in shell includes.</li><li>Using the capital letters（大写字母） to show constants.</li><li>Avoiding using space(when assign a variable, don’t use space beside the “&#x3D;”)</li><li>Assign a value to a variable using a statement  <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">for file in `ls /etc`</span><br><span class="line">OR</span><br><span class="line">for file in $(ls /etc)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li></ol></li><li><p>Using a variable:</p><ol><li>By adding ‘$’ before the name of the variable <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">my_name=&quot;New Jeans&quot;</span><br><span class="line">echo $my_name</span><br><span class="line">echo $&#123;my_name&#125;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure> The {} outside the variable name are optional, and you can choose to add them or not. Adding curly braces helps the interpreter identify the boundaries of the variable, as in the following case <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">for skill in Ada Coffe Action Java; do</span><br><span class="line">    echo &quot;I am good at $&#123;skill&#125;Script&quot;</span><br><span class="line">done</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li></ol></li><li><p>Read-only variable</p><ol><li>the code below will get:<code>/bin/sh: NAME: This variable is read only.</code></li></ol> <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">#!/bin/bash</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">myUrl=&quot;https://www.google.com&quot;</span><br><span class="line">readonly myUrl</span><br><span class="line">myUrl=&quot;https://www.runoob.com&quot;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>Deleting a variable by <code>unset variable_name</code>(Can’t delete the read_only variables) </p></li><li><p>Types of variables</p><ol><li>String: <code>my_string=&#39;Hello, World!&#39;OR my_string=&quot;Hello, World!&quot;</code></li><li>Integer: using <code>declare</code> or <code>typeset</code>: declare -i my_integer&#x3D;42</li><li>Array: <code>my_array=(1 2 3 4 5)</code></li><li>Associative array:    <figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">declare -A associative_array</span><br><span class="line">associative_array[&quot;name&quot;]=&quot;John&quot;</span><br><span class="line">associative_array[&quot;age&quot;]=30    </span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li>Environment variables: For example, the PATH variable contains the paths that the operating system searches for executable files <code>echo $PATH</code></li></ol></li></ol><h2 id="Common-pitfalls-mistakes"><a href="#Common-pitfalls-mistakes" class="headerlink" title="Common pitfalls &amp; mistakes"></a>Common pitfalls &amp; mistakes</h2><h2 id="Pros-cons"><a href="#Pros-cons" class="headerlink" title="Pros &amp; cons"></a>Pros &amp; cons</h2><h2 id="Summary-further-reading"><a href="#Summary-further-reading" class="headerlink" title="Summary &amp; further reading"></a>Summary &amp; further reading</h2>]]>
    </content>
